Pardo Alcaide (
<number id="9E1ADE6CFFEAD209FE27FE60184EFE1E" box="[472,522,427,448]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1950.0">1950</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
without designation of a 
<typeStatus id="F76972E9FFEAD209FCFAFE60196AFE1E" box="[773,814,427,448]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">type</typeStatus>
species.
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="60C89FC0FFEAD209FF68FE251848FBFC" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="286DCC4BFFEAD209FF68FE251848FBFC" blockId="12.[151,1437,493,1130]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FF68FE251B4DFDDB" box="[151,265,494,517]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This subgenus is easily distinguishable from all other 
<taxonomicName id="EFD2B7C8FFEAD209FC58FE261E48FDD8" authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[935,1036,493,518]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FC58FE261E48FDD8" box="[935,1036,493,518]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Mylabris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgenera by the synapomoprhic condition of the fore modified portion of the mesosternum, usually named “scutum” in the specialized literature (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="4C43B1BAFFEAD209FF2DFDFE1BCDFD90" author="Bologna" box="[210,393,565,590]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Bologna, M. A. (1991 a) Coleoptera Meloidae. Fauna d'Italia. XXVIII. Calderini, Bologna, xiv + 541 pp." type="book" year="1991" yearSuffix="a">
Bologna, 
<number id="9E1ADE6CFFEAD209FEBEFDFD1B3FFD90" box="[321,379,566,590]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1991.0">1991</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="4C43B1BAFFEAD209FE68FDFE18E2FD90" author="Bologna" box="[407,678,565,590]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Bologna, M. A. &amp; Pinto, J. D. (2002) The Old World genera of Meloidae (Coleoptera): a key and synopsis. Journal of Natural History, 36, 2013 - 2102. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930110062318" type="journal article" year="2002">
Bologna &amp; Pinto, 
<number id="9E1ADE6CFFEAD209FD95FDFD18E2FD90" box="[618,678,566,590]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and which is characterized in its posterior central part by dense, longer setae, these setae, emerging from deep setigerous pits, are differently long in each species, but distinct from other mesosternal setae and clearly visible in both ventral and lateral view. The combination of the following other characters, which are variously assembled in other subgenera, supports the diagnosis of the subgenus: body integument black, without metallic reflexion (only some mountain populations of 
<taxonomicName id="EFD2B7C8FFEAD209FB7DFD0D1F4BFD03" authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[1154,1295,710,733]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricincta">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FB7DFD0D1F4BFD03" box="[1154,1295,710,733]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. tricincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, previously described as 
<taxonomicName id="EFD2B7C8FFEAD209FED1FD211B83FCDF" box="[302,455,746,769]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Zonabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrosuturata">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FED1FD211B83FCDF" box="[302,455,746,769]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">nigrosuturata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, have slightly blue metallic reflexion; see below); red single frontal spot present (in most species or only in some populations) or absent; middle antennomeres, IX–XI not asymmetrically wider than long; pronotum without a middle longitudinal furrow, with more or less distinct fore and middle depressions; mesosternal suture usually complete and well visible; elytra brown-red with or without black spots or fasciae; ventral side of dorsal blade of claws smooth. The aedeagal distal hook is apical or subapical in position, usually not very far from apex; exceptions are 
<taxonomicName id="EFD2B7C8FFEAD209FDDEFC551897FC6B" authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[545,723,926,949]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiceguttata">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FDDEFC551897FC6B" box="[545,723,926,949]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. apiceguttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EFD2B7C8FFEAD209FD1DFC551938FC68" authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[738,892,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barezensis">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FD1DFC551938FC68" box="[738,892,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. barezensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="EFD2B7C8FFEAD209FC44FC551E0FFC68" authority="Fabricius, 1775" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[955,1099,925,950]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Mylabris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batnensis">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FC44FC551E0FFC68" box="[955,1099,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">M. batnensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(all marked by * in the text), in which the distal hook is far from the apex. For this character and other discussed in the remarks section of each species, they are tentatively referred to the nominate subgenus, but taxonomic changes could be possible after molecular phylogenetic analyses.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="60C89FC0FFEAD209FF38FBE61BFFFBB4" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="286DCC4BFFEAD209FF38FBE61BFFFBB4" blockId="12.[151,1437,493,1130]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="1AA61059FFEAD209FF38FBE61B14FB98" box="[199,336,1069,1094]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Distribution</emphasis>
. Mediterranean countries and southern Europe, Near and Middle East, from Central Asia to western 
<collectingCountry id="50C58CDBFFEAD209FF0AFB9A1B7CFBB4" box="[245,312,1105,1130]" name="China" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">China</collectingCountry>
(Xinjiang).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
